                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i><br />By contrast, you based your numbers on <b>a froglok warrior</b>.  You should have just picked a gnome.  One of the big advantages that warriors have is racial choice.  The best pick for a paladin is a dwarf.  The best overall pick for a warrior is an ogre.  That's a big, big difference.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">At the end, everyone, no matter what race, will hit 305/305/305/305. Race is moot.<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i><br />That makes no sense, Azumaan.  Let me expand on my point, because I don't understand what you are saying at all.<br /><br />The author of the post you cite says that warriors have about 100 DPS with a Windblade.  He says that warrior have only 60 DPS with one-handed weapons (a number that he just pulls out of his ass, but let's accept it).  He then says that warriors have to use one-handers to hold taunt (a highly debatable proposition, but let's accept it).  Therefore, he reasons that a warrior can only do 60 DPS because of the taunt issue (which confuses taunt with snap aggro, but let's accept it).  He then says that paladins can do about 88 DPS with a Windblade (a number that he just pulls out of his ass, but let's accept it).  So therefore paladins have an advantage over warriors by 88 to 60.<br /><br />Now, let's suppose that SOE gave warriors snap aggro.  That would mean that warriors can return to doing 100 DPS.  Paladins would still have 88 DPS.  That means that warriors would have a sizable DPS advantage and equal taunt ability.  Adios, paladins.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">That's exactly what I said. And if you reread more carefully this time, you will see that Warriors DO NOT WANT to be as good or better than Knights at snap-aggro, we just want to be comparble to them. Warriors do still have a small edge in damage absorption, mitigation, and DPS. Knights deserve an edge in snap-aggro, but not the double or nothing that they have now.<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i><br />But even with self-serving methodology, the author of that post concludes that paladins have 12% less DPS.  Sorry, but that number is not minimal, and the real number is probably higher -- more like 25% -- when you include the difference in Offense.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">Is it just me, or are you too making numbers up out of your ass? The fact of the matter is the melee skills difference between a Knight and a Warrior is too small to serve as a basis for an argument.[q<br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i>I don't understand what you're saying.  SOE said a while back that paladins were supposed to have about 75% of the DPS of a warrior.  I don't understand what you mean by "25% Cleric/Necro."  Are we talking about the same thing?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">Warrior+Cleric=Paladin.<br />Warrior+Necro=Shadow Knight<br />Knight=Paladin and Shadow Knight<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Orginally posted by Azumaan.</i><br />It doesn't matter if I, a Warrior, have a billion HP if the mob isn't attacking me.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote