                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I'll start with Zurmakin:<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">And here your complete ignorance of the warrior class shines through. In fact Frogloks have *excellent* warrior stats. If I'd picked an ogre, the AC would have been far lower, and the HP advantage would have been a bit more.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />No, man, your total cluelessness about melees is what shines through here.  The starting stamina of a froglok is <b>forty-two points</b> lower than the starting stamina of an ogre.  Frogloks have nice agility and dexterity, but who gives a shit?  Stamina is what matters.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">You insist on ignoring the theoretical advantage warriors have, while also ignoring the experiential experience I have as a warrior. What do you want to listen to then? <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />In case you missed it, I play a warrior, too.  Unlike you, I actually understand how things like HPs, AC, and DPS work.  Personally, I'm comfortable with the real, non-hypothetical data in that post linked by Azumaan.  It toasts you.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">I didn't even mention the self-buffs paladins get that more than makes up the HP disadvantage.<br /><br />. . .<br /><br />Best warrior in my guild (me) has 6263 HP unbuffed. Best paladin in my guild has 5547 HP unbuffed. Brell's is 330 HP, Aura of the Crusader is another 350 HP, totalling 680 HP from self buffs that he gets in xp groups and I don't.<br /><br />Result? 6227 HP for him after self buffs, 6263 for me still since I don't get buffs of any sort.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Brell's is not a self-buff.  He can cast it on you.  Aura of the Crusader does not stack with shaman buffs like Focus, though it presumably stacks with Infusion of Spirit (just like Shield of Maelin and BAotR).  Brell's makes up some of the HP difference (given that warriors will usually not have a paladin in their group), but Aura of the Crusader is pretty much irrelevant.<br /><br />I have no way of judging whether your gear is really comparable to your paladin guildie.  The data in the post linked by Azumann looks like a pretty fair "apples to apples" comparison that isn't based on just two particular characters.<br /><br />Now for Azumaan:<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">At the end, everyone, no matter what race, will hit 305/305/305/305. Race is moot.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />That may be true for fairly high end players, but it's not true for the majority of players.  Furthermore, starting stats influence gear choices throughout the life of a character.  Sure, a froglok can make up the 42 point stamina deficit to an ogre with lots of stamina gear, but that probably means that the froglok is sacrificing AC, HPs, or other stats.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">That's exactly what I said. And if you reread more carefully this time, you will see that Warriors DO NOT WANT to be as good or better than Knights at snap-aggro, we just want to be comparble to them. Warriors do still have a small edge in damage absorption, mitigation, and DPS. Knights deserve an edge in snap-aggro, but not the double or nothing that they have now.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I agree with a lot of that, though I don't think the warrior's edge is "small."  (And I don't know what you mean by "the double or nothing.")  However, you touch on the core of the problem: how could you ever make warrior snap aggro "comparable" to paladin snap aggro, but not "as good" as paladin snap aggro?  If snap aggro isn't reliable, it isn't valuable.<br /><br />It's not impossible to come up with a fix, but it's a lot easier for SOE to just ignore the problem.  And that is what has happened.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Is it just me, or are you too making numbers up out of your ass? The fact of the matter is the melee skills difference between a Knight and a Warrior is too small to serve as a basis for an argument.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />It's just you.  I'm pulling numbers out of the post that <b>you</b> linked on this board.  The fact is that the evidence showing a melee skills difference between knights and warriors is so overpowering that all you can do is pretend that it doesn't exist.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">However, in order to be a tank, the mob has to be fighting you, not the Healers and Slowers. As I said, if I had 1,000,000,000 HP, it wouldn't matter because the mob would be ping-ponging between the Healer and Slower.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />You seem to be getting confused, so let me see if I can get you back on track.  We both agree that warriors have a problem with snap aggro.  We both agree that warrior HPs do not help the warrior taunt the mob.<br /><br />What we are discussing is the effect on paladins and SKs if warriors got snap aggro (or even some "comparable but not as good as" snap aggro).  Zurmakin said that paladins would be fine because they have equivalent DPS, HPs, and defensive skills to warriors.  I showed that he was wrong, and that paladins would therefore suffer if they lost their snap aggro advantage.<br /><br />You are now returning to the fact that warriors have a problem with snap aggro.  Well, duh.  But we're past that stage of the discussion.  We're talking about what would happen if warriors were given snap aggro.<br /><br />As an aside, I missed another error that Zurmakin made.  He said that paladins are equivalent to warriors defensively.  While it is true the paladins get the same cap for Defense, warriors have a higher cap for Parry (by 25), Dodge (by 20), and Riposte (by 25).  I've never seen any data on the effect of those higher caps, but that's a fairly large difference.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Again, you do realize that I AM a Warrior right? I know what I am talking about because I have experienced the suck that is being a Warrior FIRST FREAKING HAND.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Yes, and I think you've lost your ability to look at this issue with any measure of objectivity.  I play a warrior, too, you know.  I know exactly what the taunt problems are like.  I also know that a lot of warriors have worked themselves into a lather trying to convince themselves that the class totally sucks.  You will find the same thing on this board about necromancers.<br /><br />Warriors have a problem with snap aggro.  It's bad enough that I avoid playing my warrior alt and instead play my necromancer as much as I can.  The problem needs to be fixed.  The trick is to fix the problem without sending paladins and SKs back to where they were two years ago.  When you and Zurmakin try to say that warriors would not have a big advantage over paladins and SKs if they had snap aggro (or something "comparable but not as good as" snap aggro), you are just kidding yourselves.  The actual data toasts your arguments.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
