                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i><br />Now for Azumaan:<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">At the end, everyone, no matter what race, will hit 305/305/305/305. Race is moot.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">That may be true for fairly high end players, but it's not true for the majority of players.  Furthermore, starting stats influence gear choices throughout the life of a character.  Sure, a froglok can make up the 42 point stamina deficit to an ogre with lots of stamina gear, but that probably means that the froglok is sacrificing AC, HPs, or other stats.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">My Warrior (Half Elf) has the following naked stats: 80str 85sta 115agi 85dex. Yes, 115agi. I don't have any PP AAs yet, but I hit 280/271/280/280 with a Shaman or Beastlord around. Note that my STA isn't capped, but it would be if I knew what I was doing a little over 3 years ago when I created this (my second) character. (Truth be told, I thought AGI would make me run faster.) I haven't "sacrificed" anything to boost my STA, it comes from the gear I wear, which is nothing special (no ornate, no Velious gear higher than SS).<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i><br />I agree with a lot of that, though I don't think the warrior's edge is "small."  (And I don't know what you mean by "the double or nothing.")  However, you touch on the core of the problem: how could you ever make warrior snap aggro "comparable" to paladin snap aggro, but not "as good" as paladin snap aggro?  If snap aggro isn't reliable, it isn't valuable.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">The only real remaining edge Warrior's have over Knight's tanking is defensive/evasive. I, for one, and I know many others agree with me, would gladly share these discs for a peice of snap aggro. I was at a loss for words when I said "double or nothing," but I basically meant that it's not fair for Knights to have <b>all</b> of the snap aggro eggs in their basket.<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i>It's not impossible to come up with a fix, but it's a lot easier for SOE to just ignore the problem.  And that is what has happened.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">Nope, sure isn't, which is why this thread is on it's 7th page and this discussion is on its collective inumerable page.<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i>It's just you.  I'm pulling numbers out of the post that <b>you</b> linked on this board.  The fact is that the evidence showing a melee skills difference between knights and warriors is so overpowering that all you can do is pretend that it doesn't exist.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">Erm, what evidence?<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen</i><br />You seem to be getting confused, so let me see if I can get you back on track.  We both agree that warriors have a problem with snap aggro.  We both agree that warrior HPs do not help the warrior taunt the mob.<br /><br />What we are discussing is the effect on paladins and SKs if warriors got snap aggro (or even some "comparable but not as good as" snap aggro).  Zurmakin said that paladins would be fine because they have equivalent DPS, HPs, and defensive skills to warriors.  I showed that he was wrong, and that paladins would therefore suffer if they lost their snap aggro advantage.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">You need to be careful to understand the distinction between Knight, Paladin, and Shadow Knight. Knight is both of the latter, and it is what is in contention. I agree that Knights do not have <i>equivalent</i> defensive skills as Warriors, but they are so close that the difference is almost invisible. I won't pretend to hide the fact that the Knight grouping frenzy will slacken when Warrior's are brought up to speed. As it stands, Knights are TOO good. Warrior's being marginally equivocalized will only balance out the Who can Tank? question so that any of the 3 classes able will have the same chance of being chose for the duty. Of course, that's not quite fair, because Warrior's still have the raid advantage, so Warrior's can't be as good as Knights.<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen.</i><br />As an aside, I missed another error that Zurmakin made.  He said that paladins are equivalent to warriors defensively.  While it is true the paladins get the same cap for Defense, warriors have a higher cap for Parry (by 25), Dodge (by 20), and Riposte (by 25).  I've never seen any data on the effect of those higher caps, but that's a fairly large difference.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">See Zurmakin's post for this. In summary: a very small percentage of attacks are actually Parried/Dodged/Riposted. I don't have factual numbers, but I can tell you that the difference here is miniscule.<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Originally posted by Sleppen.</i><br />Yes, and I think you've lost your ability to look at this issue with any measure of objectivity.  I play a warrior, too, you know.  I know exactly what the taunt problems are like.  I also know that a lot of warriors have worked themselves into a lather trying to convince themselves that the class totally sucks.  You will find the same thing on this board about necromancers.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">I don't think we think suck, I think we're mad because everyone else does (but they are finally learning otherwise).<blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><i>Orginally posted by Sleppen.</i><br />Warriors have a problem with snap aggro.  It's bad enough that I avoid playing my warrior alt and instead play my necromancer as much as I can.  The problem needs to be fixed.  The trick is to fix the problem without sending paladins and SKs back to where they were two years ago.  When you and Zurmakin try to say that warriors would not have a big advantage over paladins and SKs if they had snap aggro (or something "comparable but not as good as" snap aggro), you are just kidding yourselves.  The actual data toasts your arguments.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote">All the data I've seen shows that Warrior's have a small advantage over Knights and that the biggest problem of Knight's snap-aggro (which they have always had) is that now they can tank so close to as well as a Warrior can, their snap-aggro has an entirely different meaning. It went from an ability that didn't mean anything because Knight's were made of paper to a game-breaking role reversal.<br /><br />Here's my summary of our argument:<ul><li>Azumaan thinks that Knight DPS is close to Warrior's due to the superior ratios available on Knight-only weapons and their self-imbue procs (<- new point). Sleppen disagrees because Knight weapon skills cap 25 points lower and Offense 27 points lower. (by the way, that only gives Knights 156 less ATK than Warrior's, each skill point gives +3 ATK (<- new point).</li><li>Azumaan thinks Warrior's are only slightly better tanks than Knights (because of higher AC, HP, Parry/Dodge/Riposte caps) and that Warrior's gain no major advantage because of this. Sleppen thinks Knight's are at a major disadvantage to Warrior's because of their lower-capping avoidance skills and HP/AC.</li><li>Azumaan thinks that, since Knights are so close in their ability to tank as Knights, their monopoly on aggro is unfair. Sleppen thinks they deserve it since they suck at tanking (worse mitigation, few hundred less HP, 20-25 point lower caps).</li><li>Azumaan knows that Warrior's have a special place on raids that Knights simply cannot fill and Knights need some kind of bone to keep them happy. Sleppen knows this too.</li><li>Azumaan thinks that Warrior's need to have some snap-aggro, but not as good as Knights. Sleppen doesn't think this is possible</li></ul>I know I missed some stuff and generalized a bit. If it doens't make complete since, I'm sorry - I walked away from the computer amidst writing that and probably lost my train of thought.<br /><br />Anyway, the most important bit is the last one - whether or not Warrior's can get snap aggro that is enticing enough for Warrior's to get back into groups, but not so enticing as to throw Knights back into the cold where they should not be.<br /><br />It also seems like there is something I am forgetting to mention. If it's obvious, I'm sure someone will point it out and I'll hit it then. :)<br /><br />EDIT: Oh ya, your most recent post, Sleppen.<br /><br />You talk about how it isn't possible for Warriors to get snap aggro without killing Knight's role in tanking for EXP groups. Their existence will remain because of Paladin stuns, group heals, Brell's, root, etc. and Shadow Knight snares, pet dps, dot dps,  VERY quick casting nukes (good gate-stoppers), group taps, life taps, FD etc. Yes, these have always existed, but they were never given a proper light to shine because Knights were such crappy tanks back then. Now that they are good tanks, these abilties are becoming more relied on by groups and when Warrior's get some snap aggro, groups will start inviting Warrior's again, but they (the group members) will miss all of the things mentioned above that Knights contribute and a proper balance between effeciency (Warrior) and ease/relaxation (Knight) should be achieved when groups decided what type of group they want to have.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
