                      <td colspan="2" valign="top">
                      <img src="images/icon_mi_1.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="" title="" hspace="3" /><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;10/06/2003&nbsp;:&nbsp; 1:24:43 PM</font>
                      &nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=10646"><img src="images/icon_profile.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Show Profile" title="Show Profile" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      <hr noshade size="2"></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Erm, what evidence?<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />This is appalling.  Did you even <b>read</b> the post that you linked on this board?  It lays out the evidence pretty well.  The author of the post has a lot of spin-doctoring to try to make it seem that warriors suck, but the evidence is all there.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">I agree that Knights do not have equivalent defensive skills as Warriors, but they are so close that the difference is almost invisible.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />You keep saying that, but you offer no support for it.  The real, non-hypothetical data shows a difference of about 1000 HPs and 100 AC at the high end, and caps on parry, dodge, and riposte that are 20-25 points higher.<br /><br />As for your half-elf warrior, you are now talking about buffed stats, while Zurmakin was talking about unbuffed stats.  Furthermore, the question is not whether your warrior had to make sacrifices, but instead is whether a paladin has to make sacrifices.  The author of the post you link made an "apples to apples" comparison of top-level warriors and paladins, and found big differences in HPs and AC.  Just out of curiosity, how do you explain that?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">See Zurmakin's post for this. In summary: a very small percentage of attacks are actually Parried/Dodged/Riposted. I don't have factual numbers, but I can tell you that the difference here is miniscule.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Zurmakin's post has no data on this.  I'm confident that the difference is not miniscule, but I have no data on the magnitude of the effect.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Azumaan thinks that Knight DPS is close to Warrior's due to the superior ratios available on Knight-only weapons and their self-imbue procs (&lt;- new point). Sleppen disagrees because Knight weapon skills cap 25 points lower and Offense 27 points lower. (by the way, that only gives Knights 156 less ATK than Warrior's, each skill point gives +3 ATK (&lt;- new point).<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Knights have superior ratios on their one-handed weapons, but I've seen little evidence that knights have any significant advantage on two-handed weapons.  Yes, there are some nice knight-only two-handers.  However, when you look at the two-handers that are available to equivalent warriors, the ratios are similar.  Let me put it this way -- I am not aware of any knight two-hander that is unbalancing at any level of the game.  If there is one out there, I've just never heard of it.<br /><br />As for the skill caps, the rogue data shows that a 10 point difference in weapon skill translates to a 5-10 percent reduction in DPS.  If you extrapolate that data to the 25 point difference in weapon skills for knights, that is at least a 12.5 percent reduction in DPS.  If you add in the 27 point difference in Offense, then it is conceivable that the DPS difference is 25 percent, which is what SOE has said that it intends.  I haven't seen any data that draws conclusions based on a difference in ATK rating, so I can't comment on that.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Azumaan thinks Warrior's are only slightly better tanks than Knights (because of higher AC, HP, Parry/Dodge/Riposte caps) and that Warrior's gain no major advantage because of this. Sleppen thinks Knight's are at a major disadvantage to Warrior's because of their lower-capping avoidance skills and HP/AC.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />That's a fair summary.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Azumaan thinks that, since Knights are so close in their ability to tank as Knights, their monopoly on aggro is unfair. Sleppen thinks they deserve it since they suck at tanking (worse mitigation, few hundred less HP, 20-25 point lower caps).<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />No, I don't think knights deserve a monopoly on snap aggro.  However, you get closer to correctly stating my views a little later, so let's skip that here.  I don't think knights suck at tanking, either, but I do think that warriors have a significant advantage aside from snap aggro.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Azumaan knows that Warrior's have a special place on raids that Knights simply cannot fill and Knights need some kind of bone to keep them happy. Sleppen knows this too.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I agree that warriors have a special place on high-level raids, but this advantage diminishes as you move down the ladder.  I don't agree with the notion that warriors can be screwed over in XP groups because they have an advantage on raids.  I suspect that you agree.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Azumaan thinks that Warrior's need to have some snap-aggro, but not as good as Knights. Sleppen doesn't think this is possible<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Actually, I said that it was not impossible.  However, it is sufficiently difficult to find a balance that SOE will probably continue to ignore the problem.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Yes, these have always existed, but they were never given a proper light to shine because Knights were such crappy tanks back then. Now that they are good tanks, these abilties are becoming more relied on by groups and when Warrior's get some snap aggro, groups will start inviting Warrior's again, but they (the group members) will miss all of the things mentioned above that Knights contribute and a proper balance between effeciency (Warrior) and ease/relaxation (Knight) should be achieved when groups decided what type of group they want to have.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Yeah, right.  Knights have not recently gone from being "crappy tanks" to being "good tanks."  The only thing that really changed was that snap aggro became important.  As of the Velious expansion, the HP/AC gap between the two classes narrowed, and warriors started bitching about it.  All of the other stuff (aside from paladin rezzes) is pretty much junk.  If you want healing, you get a healer.  If you want buffing, you get a buffer.  If you want nuking, you get a nuker.  If you want pet DPS, you get a pet class.  But if you want tanking, you get a tank.<br /><br />You are forced to speculate about what groups might do.  My view is based on what groups really did before snap aggro became such a big deal.  Who knows?  You might turn out to be right.  However, history is on my side.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
