                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">You keep saying that, but you offer no support for it. The real, non-hypothetical data shows a difference of about 1000 HPs and 100 AC at the high end, and caps on parry, dodge, and riposte that are 20-25 points higher.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />And at the VT level, it's 700 HP and about 20 AC apparently, at least in my case. Hmm, and at the low-end, it's what? 400 HP and no AC?<br /><br />You realize that a Time-equipped Knight (the high end you refer to) has no problem tanking in xp groups, right?<br /><br />You realize that a VT-equipped Knight has no problem tanking in XP groups, right?<br /><br />You additionally realize that a low-end equipped Knight has no problem tanking in most XP groups, including for sure LDoN normal adventures, right?<br /><br /><br /><br />GIVEN ALL OF THAT -- what is your basis for claiming that Knight will not be used for tanking if Warriors have an ability to hold agro that somewhat approaches a Knight's?<br /><br />Especially given that, at the low end, their buffs make up for all of the HP gap you have identified, and actually give them an AC advantage...<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Zurmakin's post has no data on this.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Actually, I said that parses showed I avoid 30% incoming blows on raid-level mobs. For instance the Bertox event, I managed to avoid (or mitigate to 0) 30% of the blows from Kings and trash both. So at most the difference in avoidance caps will affect 30% of the total damage taken. Meaning, without evidence, that if 20% of the avoidance I get is from higher avoidance caps (I think this is an extremely excessive estimate) -- then a Knight is seeing approximately 6% more damage than I am. And that's the HIGH estimate. The real winner is defensive, which reduces the damage I take by (typically) around 40%... And defensive is not often used in XP groups.<br /><br />And again, I state experientially something that should be obvious on the face of it. Knights are tanking in XP groups successfully. In fact, the groups that have Knight tanks are far more efficient than the groups that have Warrior tanks. Therefore, Knights are good tanks today.<br /><br />If Warriors were good xp tanks, it would mean that the three would compete for xp groups equally. You keep stating that this is not the case, but I have yet to see why your typical XP group would refuse to take a Knight, given that Knights are already capable of such a high level of efficiency.</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
